data.description:
As part of GG20, one of our aims is to launch Treekipedia, a repository with the goal of becoming a Tree Intelligence Commons.

While we have been working on tree models using spreadsheets and our methodology configurator, we believe that in order to achieve interoperability across platforms involved with trees, we all need to agree on the taxonomy of trees as well as the ontology for stewardship and natural capital accounting terminologies and vocabulary. We intend to transition into an open source repository and inviting a group of subject matter experts into a tree working group
data.title: Launch Treekipedia

data.reason:
Our efforts to develop an open source, comprehensive database of tree knowledge are coming along well. 

Treekipedia is launching by first combining existing and fragmented datasets into one comprehensive taxonomy and list of tree species to serve as the foundation of an extensive ontology. This ontology and tree knowledge graph will connect tree species with key characteristics, images, stewardship best practices, relevant modeling methods, geographic occurrences, bioregional aptitude, and more.



So far, we have:
Hired a post-doctorate ecologist
Developed a prototype taxonomic schema
Compiled a list of source 10+ species databases including GBIF, iNaturalist, BGCI, etc.
Created a data retrieval and filtering strategy using R Studio

Next steps:
Finish compiling and filtering species and occurrence data
Finalize and release the open source schema & ontology 
Build useful features such as tree values based on OneEarth ecoregions
Develop UI and open source contributor process (similar to Wikipedia)

There are still key questions we’re working through, and it’s important to note that Treekipedia will be ever evolving. If you want to be a part of the process reach out to @metafarmer on Telegram

data.description:
This round aims to strengthen the Hypercerts Ecosystem to realize the vision of an interconnected impact funding network. We specifically want to support projects
1. that integrate hypercerts into existing funding platforms—similar to the hypercerts integration with Gitcoin,
2. that develop new applications like prize competitions leveraging the hypercerts infrastructure,
3. that build tooling to extent the functionality for multiple integrations and applications, such as Deresy to coordinate evaluators, or
4. that are tangible use cases piloting new functionalities, e.g. implementing retroactive funding rounds with hypercerts or using hyperboards.

data.name: Regen Coordination
data.description: The Regen Coordination Round is a proposal for a GG21 community round centered on the themes of Coordi-nations 3, Cosmo-localism 2, Bio-Regionalism 3, and Regenerative Finance (ReFi) 3. Bringing together GreenPill Network 1, ReFi DAO 1, Celo Regional DAOs 1 and Regens Unite 1, we aim to support a global movement of regenerative communities leveraging Web3 for real-world impact and addressing local needs. The round will feed into a program to support the further development of local community impact tracking methodologies, grant tooling interoperability, and integrated QF & RPGF. We have currently secured $60K in funding from Celo Public Goods, ReFi DAO and Greenpill and ask for Gitcoin’s backing as we embark on a shared mission to showcase how community coordination, Web3, and innovative financial mechanisms can enable ecological and social regeneration on a global scale.

How does your project contribute to the growth of the OSS ecosystem? Please provide specific examples of how your application enhances or expands the current ecosystem.
questions.explanation:
Silvi and Treekipedia contribute significantly to the growth of the open-source software (OSS) ecosystem by providing innovative tools and a knowledge commons that empower decentralized reforestation efforts while fostering collaboration, transparency, and scalability. Built on open-source principles, they enhance the OSS ecosystem by addressing environmental challenges through accessible technology and community-driven development. Below, I’ll outline how they contribute broadly and provide specific examples of how they enhance or expand the current ecosystem.

Broad Contributions to the OSS Ecosystem
Open Access and Collaboration: Silvi’s platform and Treekipedia’s tree intelligence database are designed to be open-source, inviting global contributors—developers, scientists, and stewards—to refine and expand the tools. This aligns with OSS goals of democratizing access and encouraging collaborative innovation.
Interoperability: By integrating with existing biodiversity datasets (e.g., GBIF, iNaturalist) and blockchain frameworks (e.g., Celo, Ethereum), Silvi and Treekipedia enhance the OSS ecosystem’s interoperability, enabling seamless data sharing and functionality across platforms.
Community Empowerment: Silvi’s mobile-first app and Treekipedia’s knowledge graph lower barriers for non-technical users (e.g., tree stewards, farmers) to engage with OSS, expanding the ecosystem’s reach beyond traditional developer communities.
Sustainability Focus: They introduce a purpose-driven OSS model, linking software development to real-world ecological impact, which can inspire other OSS projects to tackle global challenges like climate change.
Specific Examples of Enhancement and Expansion
Silvi App as an Open-Source MRV Tool
Enhancement: The Silvi App, currently in open beta, serves as a Monitoring, Reporting, and Verification (MRV) tool for reforestation. It enhances the OSS ecosystem by providing a decentralized, gamified platform for tracking tree planting—something rare in existing OSS tools. Its integration with blockchain (e.g., Celo for payments in cUSD/USDC) adds a secure, transparent layer to OSS applications, advancing the ecosystem’s capability in financial and ecological accountability.
Expansion: By offering an open-source MRV framework, Silvi invites developers to adapt it for other environmental projects (e.g., soil health, water conservation), potentially spawning new OSS tools. For instance, its methodology configurator—defining proof-of-tree events like germination or planting—could be repurposed for broader ecological monitoring.
Treekipedia’s Knowledge Graph and Ontology
Enhancement: Treekipedia consolidates fragmented tree data into a structured, AI-enhanced repository with over 50,000 species and 17.6 million records. This enhances the OSS ecosystem by providing a robust, open-access knowledge base that other projects (e.g., ecological modeling tools) can build upon, reducing redundancy and improving data quality.
Expansion: Its use of Blazegraph for querying and IPFS for decentralized storage introduces advanced OSS infrastructure to the ecosystem. Developers can leverage these technologies for other decentralized databases, expanding OSS applications beyond reforestation—say, into open-source genomics or climate data platforms.
TreeForwards and Batch Accounting
Enhancement: Silvi’s TreeForwards—a fractional funding model tied to verifiable milestones—enhances the OSS ecosystem by integrating economic incentives into open-source software. The batch accounting system, managing groups of TreeForwards, improves scalability, a common challenge in OSS, making it a blueprint for large-scale project management tools.
Expansion: This financial coordination model could inspire new OSS projects in impact investing or decentralized finance (DeFi), where verifiable outcomes trigger payments. For example, an open-source platform for renewable energy credits could adopt a similar structure.
Community-Driven Validation and Incentives
Enhancement: Silvi’s peer review system for planting verification and Treekipedia’s Contreebution NFTs (~$3 to sponsor species research) enhance OSS by embedding community governance and incentivization—key trends in modern OSS like GitHub’s contributor models. This strengthens ecosystem trust and participation.
Expansion: The NFT-based incentive model expands OSS by blending Web3 innovations with environmental goals, potentially leading to new OSS frameworks for tokenized contributions in education, healthcare, or conservation.
Real-World Impact Example
In Kenya, Silvi’s OSS tools have supported the propagation of over 150,000 trees in Kakamega Forest, with the app enabling local stewards to document and verify plantings. Treekipedia’s species data ensures these efforts use native trees suited to the biome. This demonstrates how Silvi and Treekipedia enhance OSS by delivering practical, scalable solutions while inviting global developers to refine the codebase—e.g., adapting it for other forests or urban green spaces.

questions.query: What features or use cases does your dApp/App present? How is it differentiated?
questions.explanation:
Features and Use Cases of Silvi dApp and Treekipedia
Silvi dApp Features and Use Cases:

TreeForwards: Fractional funding units for reforestation, enabling sponsors to support specific trees with milestone-based payments (e.g., planting, survival) tied to verified outcomes.
MRV Tool: A mobile-first, open beta app for Monitoring, Reporting, and Verification, allowing stewards to geotag and document tree planting, with blockchain-backed claims for transparency.
Batch Accounting: Manages groups of TreeForwards efficiently, ensuring scalability for large-scale projects while tracking individual tree care.
Payments via Blockchain: Integrates with Celo and other EVM-compatible chains, issuing payouts in stablecoins (cUSD, USDC) to stewards and verifiers upon claim approval.
Community-Driven Validation: Peer review system for verifying planting claims, fostering trust and participation.
Use Case: In Kenya, Silvi has propagated 150,000+ trees in Kakamega Forest, empowering 200+ users (schools, farmers) to manage nurseries and earn via verified milestones.

Treekipedia Features and Use Cases:

Comprehensive Tree Database: An open-source repository with 50,000+ species and 17.6 million records, offering ecological, taxonomic, and stewardship data.
AI Research Agents: Autonomously compile and refine tree knowledge, pinned to IPFS with Ethereum Attestation Service for credibility.
Contreebution NFTs: Users fund species research (~$3 each), receiving NFTs as proof of contribution, incentivizing participation.
Knowledge Graph: Structured ontology for querying species-specific best practices, enhancing reforestation planning.
Use Case: Treekipedia supports Silvi stewards by providing native species data for Kakamega, ensuring climate-adapted planting.

Differentiation
Silvi: Unlike traditional reforestation platforms, Silvi combines blockchain transparency, fractional funding, and gamified MRV, making tree planting accessible and verifiable. It stands out from carbon credit platforms by focusing on individual tree stewardship rather than offsets alone.
Treekipedia: Differentiates from static biodiversity databases (e.g., GBIF) with its AI-driven, community-updated model and Web3 incentives, creating a living, decentralized "Wikipedia for trees" tailored for actionable reforestation insights.
Together, they offer a unique, tech-forward ecosystem that bridges funding, knowledge, and action, distinct from centralized or less interactive alternatives.

questions.query: What are your plans for further development, and how will the grant funds be used to achieve these goals?
questions.explanation:
Plans for Further Development of Silvi and Treekipedia
Silvi:

Enhanced MRV Capabilities: Integrate advanced remote sensing (e.g., drones, satellites) and statistical sampling to improve verification accuracy and scale monitoring across larger reforestation projects.
Tokenomics and Governance: Launch a native governance token and DAO structure to decentralize portfolio management, enabling community-led decision-making for global reforestation efforts.
Carbon and Eco-Credit Integration: Connect Silvi with carbon credit issuers and ecological frameworks (e.g., Ecological Benefits Framework) to unlock additional revenue streams for stewards and investors.
Global Expansion: Grow OperationWebTree beyond its 18 current partners, targeting 100+ community projects worldwide, with a focus on urban re-greening and agroforestry.
Treekipedia:

AI Scaling: Develop advanced AI agents for ecological modeling and automated knowledge updates, enhancing real-time species data accuracy.
Decentralized Governance: Introduce DeepTrees NFT collections (e.g., Iconic Species NFTs) to fund research and guide Treekipedia’s evolution through community governance.
API and Partnerships: Launch a public API for integration with research platforms and forge global partnerships with biodiversity institutions to expand data interoperability.
Community Engagement: Form working groups with scientists and stewards to refine methodologies and validate data, making Treekipedia a collaborative hub.
